  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book \"Mapping Landscapes in Transformation,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2019, has established its presence in the academic discourse, albeit with limited visibility in public and community platforms.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Mapping Landscapes in Transformation\" serves as a significant scholarly contribution to understanding the dynamic nature of landscapes within transformative contexts. Despite a citation count of zero, the work has been recognized within various frameworks of academic discourse and has potential relevance for discussions around landscape changes.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The estimated engagement with the work suggests a positive, albeit limited, trajectory. The strength of the inferred role of 'active public discourse' showcases that the book has engaged a total of 12 events, indicating some level of interest and usage within academic and possibly the early stages of public conversation.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The inference of 'commercial linkage' indicates that the work is available on notable platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, hinting at interest beyond strictly academic audiences. This can be viewed as an opportunity to further the book's outreach to a broader audience interested in the themes of transformation within landscapes.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">With a strong emphasis on scholarly uptake, albeit modest, the work's potential to contribute to ongoing discussions in its field remains intact. Engaging new audiences by enhancing its visibility could foster greater academic collaboration and public interest in the ideas presented within. As such, while its metrics indicate an initial phase of engagement, there is room for growth and advocacy to elevate its scholarly conversation.</p>",
